{
  "text": "Besides IL-6 and IL-10, AC-2 also reduced LPS-induced iNOS gene expression and NO release in RAW 264.7 cells. The expression inhibition of the iNOS protein responsible for NO inhibition by A camphorata had been reported [CITATION_1] . Here we suggested for the first time that A camphorata reduced LPS-induced NO production by inhibiting iNOS mRNA expression. Although nanomolar concentrations of NO play an important physiological role as a defense molecule in the immune system [CITATION_2] , overproduction of NO, predominantly via the upregulation of iNOS in macrophages, contributes to numerous pathological processes, including inflammation [CITATION_3] and atherosclerosis [CITATION_4] . The mechanism responsible for NO inhibition of several plant extracts had been reported, including direct scavenging of NO [CITATION_5] , suppression of iNOS activity [CITATION_6] , or the reduction on iNOS gene expression [CITATION_7] . In the present data, the AC-2 fraction of A camphorata expressed anti-inflammatory effects via iNOS gene inhibition. This inhibition may in part be through inhibiting LPS-activated NF-\u03baB translocation ( Figure 7B ). This data suggests that the AC-2 polysaccharide fraction of A camphorate could be an attractive candidate for adjunctive therapy in gram-negative bacterial infections.",
